rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: This pitfall appears when any relationship (except for those that are defined as symmetric properties using owl:SymmetricProperty) does not have an inverse relationship (owl:inverseOf) defined within the ontology.
A symmetric object property (owl:SymmetricProperty) is defined as inverse of another object property (using owl:inverseOf).
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Defining inverse relationships for a symmetric one

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: Ontology elements (classes, object properties and datatype properties) are created isolated, with no relation to the rest of the ontology.
A relationship is defined as inverse of itself. In this case, this relationship could have been defined as owl:SymmetricProperty instead.
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Defining a relationship as inverse to itself

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: This pitfall consists in missing the definition of equivalent classes (owl:equivalentClass) in case of duplicated concepts. When an ontology reuses terms from other ontologies, classes that have the same meaning should be defined as equivalent in order to benefit the interoperability between both ontologies.

This pitfall consists in creating an ontology element and failing to provide human readable annotations attached to it. Consequently, ontology elements lack annotation properties that label them (e.g. rdfs:label, lemon:LexicalEntry, skos:prefLabel or skos:altLabel) or that define them (e.g. rdfs:comment or dc:description). This pitfall is related to the guidelines provided in [5].

The relationship "is" is created in the ontology instead of using OWL primitives for representing the subclass relationship (rdfs:subClassOf), class membership (rdf:type), or the equality between instances (owl:sameAs). When concerning a class hierarchy, this pitfall is related to the guidelines for understanding the "is-a" relation provided in [2].
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Creating the relationship "is" instead of using "rdfs:subClassOf", "rdf:type" or "owl:sameAs"

rdf:Description.oops:hasAffectedElement: There are elements following different naming conventions as for example: http://mmv.eecs.qmul.ac.uk/lasie/Perdurant/endurant.owl#Mojahedin-eKhalq http://mmv.eecs.qmul.ac.uk/lasie/Perdurant/endurant.owl#NonPhysicalEndurant
rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The ontology elements are not named following the same convention (for example CamelCase or use of delimiters as "-" or "_") . Some notions about naming conventions are provided in [2].
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Using different naming conventions in the ontology

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: Object and/or datatype properties without domain or range (or none of them) are included in the ontology.
rdf:Description.oops:hasName: Missing domain or range in properties

rdf:Description.oops:hasDescription: The ontology lacks information about equivalent properties (owl:equivalentProperty) in the cases of duplicated relationships and/or attributes.

An ontology element (a class, an object property or a datatype property) is used in its own definition. Some examples of this would be: (a) the definition of a class as the enumeration of several classes including itself; (b) the appearance of a class within its owl:equivalentClass or rdfs:subClassOf axioms; (c) the appearance of an object property in its rdfs:domain or range rdfs:range definitions; or (d) the appearance of a datatype property in its rdfs:domain definition.
The domain and range axioms are equal for each of the following object properties. Could they be symmetric or transitive?
rdf:Description.oops:hasCode: SUGGESTION: symmetric or transitive object properties.
